Posted: Thu Dec 06, 2007 11:02 am
quote:Originally posted by Auritania:IT people and computer programmers are NOT the people to design your logistics system. Clever and elegant to them always equates to disaster in the warehouse. What pinhead decided that return requests should use the order system with the user entering negatives instead of positives? Think about it.... open shipping window, enter negative quantities and voila! elegant solution to creating a dedicated returns form. Brilliant!! So far 2 out of 3 returns have ended up as orders because people don't remember to put that little negative sign in front. But it gets better!So your return ends up being a ship order. The customer gets double what they don't want. Ok, create ANOTHER return order. Christ on a pogo stick! They forgot that minus sign again on 1/2 the returns!! Now, customers have FOUR TIMES as much to return. But, here is the sexy part. You coders were really clever and coded the system to not print any orders with less than 1 item. Lets see... -100 is less than 1. Hmmm... business is very good! Customers haven't returned anything and lots of them are ordering twice or four times as much as usual!!Ok, pinhead, reality sets in. What's your elegant solution to the problem? Oh, yeah... have someone use PrtScr to get a snapshot of the order screen showing the minus amounts and fax those printouts to the warehouses. That worked really well. All those pretty colors and cool graphics on the order screen? Then don't show up in black and white. Yup. Paper, pencil and fax machine to the rescue. Did I mention that we get the same orders dropped to us randomly every 3-5 days? Or that Tampa is shipping to San Francisco and San Francisco seems to only get orders for Detroit? Detroit doesn't mind. They are being told to duplicate the orders.Your $5M upgrade has been reduced to people faxing handwritten notes to each other. Transportation costs have increased over $400k per month. Customer satisfaction is in the basement. Inventory is so out of control that the system shows $25M less in inventory than what you bought and receivables have jumped from 30 days to beyond 90. Your IT consultants would seem to be the only ones making any money. Their solution? Find new warehouses. Wow. Stories like this make me feel really good about the work that I do.I have a LOT of "digital duct-tape" that I've written and deployed for a variety of reasons, and some of it I consider rather embarrasing, even if it does do the job. Sometimes quality takes a back seat to 'get this fixed NOW' or 'stop wasting your time working on system X'.But even the WORST stuff I've written is miles better than this.
